A Neural Network from Scratch

Anne
June 29th 2017

What is a Neural Network?

The neuron

Mathematical Model

Example:

Inputs: salt, apple
Weights: a lot, a little, 1
Function: amplify

(a lot) * salt + 1 * apple –> alert

(a little) * salt + 1 * apple –> nothing

The Network

The Data

MNIST:
hand-written digits
28 * 28 pixels
each pixel associated with its grey level from 0 (white) to 255 (black)

How it Learns

Forward and back propagation.

Learning details

Needs previously labelled data.
Can adjust many parameters. Why ?
If the model stops too early, it does not give good results.
If the model stops too late, it does not give good results. The model is so well adjusted to the data at hand it does not generalize well.

Output
After learning, we get the best weights.
Then we can use those weights on new data and predict the output.

Tuning Parameters

Many factors can be adjusted to get better results.

Here I played with a training set of 3000 numbers and a test set of 500.
I kept the hidden layer at 25 neurons and trained the neural network only once for each case.
I varied the number of iterations from 25 to 250.
And I changed the regularization factor from 0 to 11.

Results

Training set

Test set

Results (bis)

The best results are:

  • for the training set
    0.924 with a regularisation of 10.2 and 250 iterations.
  • for the test set
    0.91 with a regularisation of 9.8 and 200 iterations.

How I did it

I started with Coursera Machine Learning class.
The 4th assignment is a step by step to make a simple neural network in Octave.
I started from there and converted (and improved) what I had done years ago in C++.

Libraries I used:

  • Armadillo for linear algebra.
    Do not loop!
  • NLopt for the optimization.

What I learned

Do not start C++ this way.
Learning curve

What I learned (continued)

C++ seems more permissive than C.
Reading what Linus Torvald said about it makes completely sense.
Syntax is actually O::K.

Once the Neural Network written, parameters tuning takes a looong time, needs a lot of memory.
It is another project in itself.
